    "text": "further verified and refined the fix commit datasets for both V-SZZ and VERJava based on GitHub issues and official project websites. As a result, we obtained a total of 273 fix commits. For each CVE within a project, we analyze all tags to identify vulnerable versions. Ground Truth. We found that the V-SZZ and VERJava datasets share 23 overlapping CVEs. However, for 18 of these, the ground truth of vulnerable versions differs between the two datasets. Both methods rely exclusively on syntax by examining only the lines modified in fix commits. V-SZZ classifies any version containing deleted lines as vulnerable, while VERJava determines vulnerable versions by comparing the code of each candidate version with both the deleted code and the added code to decide whether the vulnerability exists. In practice, such commits often include nonsecurity-related changes, such as feature enhancements or code refactoring, which can result in inaccurate identification of vulnerable versions. To address this issue, we performed a comprehensive manual validation of all 176 CVEs and identified a list of vulnerable versions for each. Our annotation principle was to identify vulnerable code based on the fundamental nature and semantics of the vulnerability. Specifically, for each CVE, we first analyze the CVE description and its associated CWE information. Drawing on expert knowledge and publicly available vulnerability- related resources, we identify the root cause of the vulnerability. We then examine the code before and after the fix to determine the vulnerable code blocks. After that, we applied git blame to trace these vulnerable lines through the version history. For each traced version, we examined whether the previous version contained the vulnerability. If not, we consider the current version to be the vulnerability-inducing version. If it did, we continued to trace the newly identified vulnerable lines further back. This recursive process was repeated until we found a version in which the vulnerability was no longer present. We define the range of vulnerable versions as the versions that span from the first identified vulnerable version to the version where the vulnerability was fixed. In total, this process resulted in a high-quality ground truth that includes 17,436 vulnerable versions in 176 CVEs. The entire manual analysis was conducted by a team consisting of one Ph.D. student with more than ten years of experience in Java vulnerability research, including the discovery of zero-day CVEs, and two master’s students. Each analyst performed in-depth research using personal experience and publicly available resources, such as official advisories and technical blogs. We use Krippendorff’s alpha [ 25 ] to measure the agreement among the three annotators. The Krippendorff’s alpha among the three annotators is 0.78, indicating a substantial agreement. The three annotators resolved the disagreements by group discussion until consensus was reached. The entire ground truth construction process took about one month.",
